---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { MACLT_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="MAC look-up table"
  description="The MACLT: the fixed sequence of tag types that lets a receiver parse a MACK without spending bits to describe it."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="3 · Data structures"
    title="The MAC look-up table"
    lead="A single byte in the DSM-KROOT picks a fixed recipe for what every tag slot in a MACK means — so the signal never has to spell it out."
  />

  <p>
    A MACK message is a list of tags, but a tag on its own does not say what kind
    of data it covers. Rather than describe each slot on the air, OSNMA agrees the
    pattern in advance. The <strong>MACLT</strong> field in the DSM-KROOT selects
    one entry from the MAC look-up table, and that entry fixes the sequence of
    <a href={withBase('/structures/mack')}>ADKD</a> types for every tag in the MACK
    <DocRef doc="icd" section="4.2" />. The sequence stays constant for as long as a
    chain is in force.
  </p>

  <h2>The table</h2>

  <ValueTable table={MACLT_TABLE} />

  <h2>Reading a sequence</h2>
  <p>Each slot in a sequence is written as a short code:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Two digits</strong> — the ADKD type: <code>00</code> for ephemeris/clock/status, <code>04</code> for timing, <code>12</code> for the slow MAC.</li>
    <li><strong>S</strong> — self-authentication: the tag covers the transmitting satellite's own data.</li>
    <li><strong>E</strong> — Galileo cross-authentication: the tag covers another Galileo satellite's data.</li>
    <li><strong>FLX</strong> — a flexible slot whose target is not fixed by the table; its Tag-Info is instead authenticated by MACSEQ <DocRef doc="rxg" section="5.5.3" />.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    So a sequence such as <code>00S, FLX, 04S, FLX, 12S, 00E</code> tells the
    receiver: the first tag is a self ephemeris tag, the third a self timing tag,
    the fifth a self slow-MAC tag, the last a cross-authentication ephemeris tag —
    and the two FLX slots may point anywhere, with MACSEQ proving the receiver read
    their Tag-Info correctly. The test vectors use <strong>MACLT = 34</strong>.
  </p>

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      Fixing the pattern is a bandwidth trick. Because both ends share the table, a
      receiver already knows what slot 3 should authenticate without the signal
      spending a single bit to say so — leaving the precious 480 bits of the MACK
      for tags and the key.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="level-engineer">
    <h3>Why flexible slots need MACSEQ</h3>
    <p>
      A fixed table cannot anticipate every operational need, so some slots are left
      flexible. But a flexible Tag-Info that nobody authenticated would be a way in
      for an attacker. MACSEQ closes that gap: it is a 12-bit MAC, computed with the
      same key as the tags, over the flexible Tag-Info fields, so the receiver can
      confirm those slots were genuinely set by Galileo
      <DocRef doc="icd" section="4.1.2" />.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
